The paper is part of the Geometric Complexity Theory series, which is focused on algebraic geometry and its applications to computational complexity. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves combinatorial and graph-theoretic arguments, which suggest cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) as likely sub-categories. The use of geometric methods and the study of geometric objects such as Schubert varieties and flag varieties suggest cs.GT (Geometric Topology) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the study of nonvanishing of coefficients, which is related to algebraic geometry and algebraic combinatorics, suggesting cs.SC (Symbolic Computation) as a possible sub-category.
